        "title": "fix #17447: [Bug]: Security audit: allow suppressing acknowledged findings + fix false positives",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Partially addresses #17447 by removing the false positive hook audit warning when request-supplied session keys are constrained by `hooks.allowedSessionKeyPrefixes`.\n- Keeps the warning when `hooks.allowRequestSessionKey=true` is enabled without prefixes, where callers can still choose arbitrary session key shapes.\n- Adds a focused regression test for the prefixed request-session-key audit configuration.\n- Why it matters / User impact: Operators can enable request-scoped hook session keys with an explicit prefix allowlist without the security audit claiming an arbitrary-session-key risk that the configured prefix boundary already prevents.\n\n## Origin / follow-up\n\nN/A — independent root cause for issue #17447, not a fan-out or merged-PR follow-up.\n\n## Root Cause\n\n- Fix classification: Root-cause fix for a security audit predicate false positive.\n- Maintainer-ready confidence: High; the diff is limited to the hook audit predicate and its focused regression coverage, and the source CLI audit path was exercised with isolated home, config, and state.\n- Root cause: `collectHooksHardeningFindings` already normalized `hooks.allowedSessionKeyPrefixes`, and the missing-prefix finding used that normalized contract, but the older `hooks.request_session_key_enabled` branch ignored the normalized prefix invariant and fired solely on `hooks.allowRequestSessionKey=true`, causing prefixed configurations to be reported as arbitrary session-key override risk.\n- Why this is root-cause fix: The fix changes the source audit invariant before findings are emitted: `hooks.request_session_key_enabled` now uses the same `allowRequestSessionKey && allowedPrefixes.length === 0` condition as the missing-prefix finding, so only configurations that permit arbitrary request session-key shapes produce the warning instead of masking the symptom after report generation.\n\n## Scope\n\n- What did NOT change: This PR does not change request routing, hook authorization, `security.audit.suppressions`, the small-model heuristic, reverse-proxy trusted-header findings, config defaults, migrations, or the public config schema. The related open PR / same-contract scan found no linked open PR for #17447 and no public-config competition PR in the evidence directory.\n- Architecture / source-of-truth check: The source-of-truth is the hook hardening audit collector that turns normalized config into security findings. This patch changes that collector predicate directly, not a report post-processor or display mirror, and it preserves backward compatibility/default behavior because unprefixed request session-key overrides continue to emit both warnings.\n- Patch quality notes: Patch-quality warnings considered: public-config surface, security-boundary, and session-state. The change is not symptom masking; it narrows one finding to the same source invariant already used by the stricter missing-prefix finding, with a two-file diff and focused regression coverage.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: `openclaw security audit --json` no longer emits `hooks.request_session_key_enabled` or `hooks.request_session_key_prefixes_missing` for a hooks config that enables request session keys but constrains them with `hooks.allowedSessionKeyPrefixes`.\n- Real environment tested: Linux source checkout, Node v22.22.0, pnpm v11.2.2, isolated `HOME`, `OPENCLAW_HOME`, `OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH`, and `OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR` under the evidence directory.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch:\n```bash\nHOME=/media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-issue-17447-evidence/audit-home \\\nOPENCLAW_HOME=/media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-issue-17447-evidence/audit-home/.openclaw \\\nOPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH=/media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-issue-17447-evidence/hooks-prefix-audit-config.json \\\nOPENCLAW_STATE_DIR=/media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-issue-17447-evidence/audit-state \\\npnpm --dir /media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-worktrees/issue-17447 exec node --import tsx -e 'import { runCli } from \"/media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-worktrees/issue-17447/src/cli/run-main.ts\"; await runCli([\"node\",\"openclaw\",\"security\",\"audit\",\"--json\"]);' \\\n> /media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-issue-17447-evidence/hooks-prefix-source-cli-audit-output.json\n\nnode -e 'const fs=require(\"fs\"); const report=JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(\"/media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-issue-17447-evidence/hooks-prefix-source-cli-audit-output.json\",\"utf8\")); const ids=new Set((report.findings||[]).map(f=>f.checkId)); for (const id of [\"hooks.request_session_key_enabled\",\"hooks.request_session_key_prefixes_missing\"]) { if (ids.has(id)) { console.error(`unexpected finding: ${id}`); process.exit(1); } } console.log(`isolated source cli audit proof ok: ${report.findings.length} findings, hook sessionKey findings absent`);'\n```\n- Evidence after fix:\n```text\nisolated source cli audit proof ok: 9 findings, hook sessionKey findings absent\n```\n- Observed result after fix: The actual source CLI `security audit --json` path completed and the parsed JSON report did not include either hook session-key finding for the prefixed configuration.\n- What was not tested: Built-package `openclaw.mjs` was not exercised because this source worktree does not include `dist/entry.mjs`; the source CLI command path was exercised instead. I did not test or change the other #17447 topics: general audit suppressions, small-model sandboxing heuristics, or reverse-proxy trusted-header warnings.\n\n## Regression Test Plan\n\n- Target test file: `src/security/audit-hooks-routing.test.ts`\n- Scenario locked in: The regression test constructs a hooks config with `allowRequestSessionKey: true` and `allowedSessionKeyPrefixes: [\"hook:\"]`, then verifies that both hook session-key findings are absent while the existing unprefixed warning coverage remains intact.\n- Why this is the smallest reliable guardrail: The test locks the audit collector behavior at the same source-of-truth predicate changed by this patch, while the source CLI proof separately exercises the real `security audit --json` command path.\n\n## Merge risk\n\n- Risk labels considered: merge risk: security-boundary, session-state, public_config.\n- Risk explanation: The touched code reports security audit findings and mentions session keys, so the risk is reviewer concern about weakening a security boundary or changing public config semantics. The patch does not relax hook authorization or routing; it only stops claiming arbitrary session-key shape risk when a configured prefix allowlist already constrains the accepted key space.\n- Why acceptable: The compatibility/default behavior is unchanged for unprefixed configurations, which continue to emit both warnings. Prefixed configurations now align both findings to the same normalized-prefix contract, and the out of scope areas are explicitly left unchanged.\n\n## Additional checks\n\n```text\ngit diff --check origin/main...HEAD\npassed with no output\n\npnpm --dir /media/vdb/code/ai/aispace/openclaw-worktrees/issue-17447 exec vitest run src/security/audit-hooks-routing.test.ts\nTest Files  1 passed (1)\nTests       14 passed (14)\n```\n",
